1. To run an example tracking fluorescent-tagged surface molecules dimerizing to become slower species on a planar surface:
   $ ecell3-session particle_tracking.py

2. To view the simulation results wth the Spatiocyte Visualizer:
   $ spatiocyte

3. To create a movie of the simulation results generated by matplotlib
   (requires matplotlib and avconv preinstalled):
   $ python ../plot/plotCoordinateLog.py

4. To view the movie, we can use the VLC player (requires VLC preinstalled):
   $ vlc CoordinateLog.csv.mov 

5. To create high quality frames with Blender, warning, this may take a lot of
   computational time (requires Blender preinstalled):
   $ blender --background --python ../blender/blender.py

6. To create a movie of those frames and view it:
   $ avconv -i image%04d.png -vcodec qtrle blender.mov
   $ vlc blender.mov

7. To increase resolution and quality of the rendering, change the following
   lines in blender_parameters.py:
   resolution_percentage = 100
   render_samples = 100
   $ blender --background --python ../blender/blender.py

8. To view microscopy snapshots of the biased walk with Spatiocyte Visualizer
   $ spatiocyte MicroscopyLog.dat

avconv -i concatenated%04d.png -s 2048x1150 -c:v libvpx -b:v 15M -crf 4 -qmin 0 -qmax 50 -threads 6 -pass 1 -an -f webm -y output.webm
avconv -i concatenated%04d.png -s 2048x1150 -c:v libvpx -b:v 15M -crf 4 -qmin 0 -qmax 50 -threads 6 -pass 2 -an -f webm -y output.webm

avconv -r 100 -i output.webm -s 2048x1150 -c:v libvpx -b:v 15M -crf 4 -qmin 0 -qmax 50 -threads 6 -pass 1 -an -f webm -y -r 100 output_r100.webm
avconv -r 100 -i output.webm -s 2048x1150 -c:v libvpx -b:v 15M -crf 4 -qmin 0 -qmax 50 -threads 6 -pass 2 -an -f webm -y -r 100 output_r100.webm
